<HL>
   What's News --
   World-Wide
</HL>
<DATE>
09/10/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   BUSH AND GORBACHEV ISSUED a joint warning to Iraq's Saddam
Hussein.
   The two leaders, meeting in Finland, told Baghdad that
they would consider unspecified "additional" steps if the
Iraqis failed to heed U.N. demands to withdraw from Kuwait.
Although Washington has said a military strike at Iraq is
still an option, Gorbachev said the Soviets wouldn't join the
land and sea forces in the Mideast, stressing the crisis must
be resolved politically.
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   Arab leaders have pledged billions of dollars to cover the
cost of U.S. forces in Saudi Arabia. Separately, as Iraq's
foreign minister met with officials in Iran over the U.N.
embargo, hundreds of foreigners left Iraq. Palestinian
radical Abul Abbas said the time might be ripe for renewed
commando warfare in support of Baghdad.
   Syria said that a series of explosions were heard in an
Iraqi border town, possibly at a chemical plant. Baghdad
denied the report from Damascus.
   ---
   Liberia's Doe was shot in both legs and captured by a
rebel faction in Monrovia, the British Broadcasting Corp.
reported. More than 60 people, including dozens of the
president's bodyguards, died in the clash with insurgents led
by Prince Johnson, who declared himself president until an
interim government can be formed, the BBC said.
   ---
   Lebanese police reported at least 75 people were killed
during a three-day offensive by the Palestine Liberation
Organization to oust guerrillas loyal to terrorist leader Abu
Nidal from Sidon and nearby refugee camps. The PLO claimed
victory against the supporters of Abu Nidal, who broke with
the PLO in 1973 to form his own group.
   ---
   Federal and state officials are preparing to demand a
third round of cleanup by Exxon next summer along the beaches
of Alaska's Prince William Sound, site of the largest oil
spill in U.S. history. More than 10 million gallons of crude
oil spilled when an Exxon tanker rammed an underwater reef in
March 1989.
   ---
   A split developed among European Community nations over
the speed and method for achieving monetary union, raising
the likelihood of difficult negotiations among members this
year. At a meeting of EC finance ministers Saturday, Britain
won unexpected support for a more cautious approach to the
issue.
   ---
   South African police opened fire to disperse crowds of
blacks in Soweto angered by an overnight attack on a squatter
camp that left at least 10 people dead. Residents accused
Zulu supporters of the conservative Inkatha movement of
launching the nighttime attack with police help.
   ---
   Lt. Gov. Evelyn Murphy took charge in Massachusetts after
Dukakis left the state on a European trade mission. In the
governor's absence, Murphy -- who is a candidate for governor
-- issued a set of budget-cutting proposals Friday that she
said could save $150 million annually. Dukakis is slated to
return late this week.
   ---
   Ontario's New Democratic Party sought to reassure a
nervous business community after the socialist party was
elected to rule the Canadian province. The party's surprise
victory Thursday is of national consequence because Ontario
accounts for over 40% of Canada's output and contains more
than a third of its people.
   ---
   Cambodia's warring groups endorsed a U.N. plan to end
their 11-year civil war, but major obstacles have yet to be
resolved. The three allied guerrilla groups and the
Vietnamese-backed Phnom Penh government concluded their first
day of peace talks yesterday in Indonesia.
   ---
   Cardiologist Bernadine Healy was chosen by Health and
Human Services Secretary Sullivan to become the director of
the National Institutes of Health. HHS officials said
Sullivan is about to choose David Kessler, medical director
of the Albert Einstein College of Medicine in New York, as
the next FDA commissioner.
   ---
   Workers and intellectuals staged a joint rally in the
central Romanian city of Brasov to protest what they said was
the government's failure to solve the country's severe
economic problems.
   ---
   Pete Sampras beat fellow American Andre Agassi in straight
sets to win the men's singles title at the U.S. Open tennis
championships. On Saturday, Gabriela Sabatini defeated Steffi
Graf in the women's final.
   ---
   Died: A.J.P. Taylor, 84, popular British historian and
journalist, Friday, in London, of Parkinson's disease.
</TEXT>
