<HL>
   International:
   Lufthansa's Interflug Bid
   Draws British Air Protest
</HL>
<DATE>
09/10/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A12
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP BAB G.LHA
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
AIRLINES (AIR)
</IN>
<LP>
   BRUSSELS -- British Airways filed a formal complaint with
the European Community Commission charging Lufthansa with
anti-competitive behavior regarding its bid for 26% of East
Germany's state-owned airline, Interflug.
   British Airways, which itself held unsuccessful talks with
Interflug this year, said, "We feel that if Lufthansa is
allowed to carry on (with its plans for the airline) it will
make free and fair competition in Germany very difficult and
will not be in the general interests of fair competition."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The West German Federal Cartel Office has said it will
object to Lufthansa's plans to take a stake in Interflug
because such an all-German combination would be dominant in
the national market. The cartel office's final ruling on the
bid is expected by the end of October.
   EC officials declined to comment on the British Airways
complaint. Lufthansa officials weren't available for comment.
   Separately, the West German magazine Der Spiegel is
expected to report that British Airways has made a bid for a
49% stake in Interflug. A British Airways spokesman said that
the company wouldn't confirm or deny the report.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900910-0010
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900910-0010.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Financial Inquiry Charges
   2 British Miners' Leaders
</HL>
<DATE>
09/10/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP LABOR
</CO>
<IN>
DIVERSIFIED MINING (MNG)
</IN>
<LP>
   LONDON (AP) -- Two top British mineworkers' leaders will
be charged with improper accounting after an inquiry into
union finances during the 1984-85 miners' strike, a court
official said.
   John Richman, a Sheffield Magistrates' Court clerk, said
he issued nine summonses against Arthur Scargill, president
of the National Union of Mineworkers, and union general
secretary Peter Heathfield, as well as against the union
itself.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The charges are failure to keep proper accounting records,
failure to maintain a satisfactory system of accounting
control and failure to submit true and fair accounts. The two
men face fines if convicted.
   "We have done nothing wrong, and we shall contest the
action all the way," Mr. Scargill said. "This is the latest
in a long line of attacks on the national leadership of the
miners' union from the establishment who have never forgiven
us for what we did in the 1984-85 miners' strike."
   Mr. Scargill led the bitter and futile showdown with the
government over the closure of unproductive mines. The union,
which had 235,000 members at the time, now has 50,000, and 98
mines have been closed.
   In July the union sued Mr. Scargill to recover #1.4
million ($2.6 million) that had been donated by Soviet and
Eastern European miners to help the British miners during the
strike.
   The court granted the union a delay while it sought to
settle the issue by negotiation. Today, a union delegation is
to go to the Paris headquarters of the International Miners'
Organization to determine control of the funds.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
